<br>
Milkchaser would likely fall into a group I would label &quot;constitutional conservatives&quot;, whereas TheRightGuy et al could best be described as &quot;Christian conservatives&quot;.<br>
<br>
MC's views and apparent philosophy falls upon the letter of what is in the Constitution and the writings of the founding fathers. TRG follows more what he perceives as the &quot;spirit&quot; of the founding fathers.<br>
<br>
&quot;Conservatism&quot;, or at least the political organization, came to the forefront in the early 60s to unite religious conservatives and constitutional conservatives against the common foe of Communism and collectivism in general. However, with Communism's death, there really seems to be little holding the two groups together. The Conservative Party's principles were listed as:<br>
...........<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That foremost among the transcendent values is the individual's use of his God-given free will, whence derives his right to be free from the restrictions of arbitrary force; <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That liberty is indivisible, and that political freedom cannot long exist without economic freedom; <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That the purpose of government is to protect those freedoms through the preservation of internal order, the provision of national defense, and the administration of justice; <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That when government ventures beyond these rightful functions, it accumulates power, which tends to diminish order and liberty; <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That the Constitution of the United States is the best arrangement yet devised for empowering government to fulfill its proper role, while restraining it from the concentration and abuse of power; <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That the genius of the Constitution- the division of powers- is summed up in the clause that reserves primacy to the several states, or to the people, in those spheres not specifically delegated to the Federal government; <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That the market economy, allocating resources by the free play of supply and demand, is the single economic system compatible with the requirements of personal freedom and constitutional government, and that it is at the same time the most productive supplier of human needs; <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That when government interferes with the work of the market economy, it tends to reduce the moral and physical strength of the nation; that when it takes from one man to bestow on another, it diminishes the incentive of the first, the integrity of the second, and the moral autonomy of both; <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That we will be free only so long as the national sovereignty of the United States is secure; that history shows periods of freedom are rare, and can exist only when free citizens concertedly defend their rights against all enemies; <br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That the forces of international Communism are, at present, the greatest single threat to these liberties; <br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That the United States should stress victory over, rather than coexistence with, this menace; and <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  That American foreign policy must be judged by this criterion: does it serve the just interests of the United States? <br>
<br>
So, aside from the acknowledgment that our free-will is God given, the &quot;official&quot; Conservative viewpoint makes no mention of a religious component. Rather, the need to preserve the Constitution AS WRITTEN, as well as the belief that a minimally restricted free market economy is essential to individual Liberty are what makes a Conservative. No dependence upon a Christian God within Government has ever been a consideration of true Conservatives. <br>
<br>
So, while I couldn't care less who actually OWNS a particular label, I think it is important that we all realize that Milkchaser's view of &quot;conservatism&quot; closely follows the tenets of the actual Conservative Party. I think it would be much better for the Conservative movement as a whole for the two groups to agree to a certain &quot;conservative&quot; orientation, but then differentiate themselves as &quot;Christian conservatives&quot; and something along the lines of &quot;Free&quot; or &quot;Constitutional&quot; conservatives. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00000F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives.showUserPublicProfile?gid=milkchaser>milkchaser</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(1/8/04 12:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: &quot;right vs. left&quot; -- is this a helpful metaphor</span><hr size=1> Yes, I am a Libertarian (and I don't think that it's very kind to call people trolls just because you disagree with them).<br>
<br>
Libertarians are usually disgruntled republicans who wish that our gov't would return to original Constitutional principles of limited gov't and federalism.<br>
<br>
Had Libertarians voted for the Republican candidates in past elections, Bush/Gore in Florida wouldn't have been a nail-biter, NV, WA &amp; SD would all have Republican Senators and the Senate wouldn't have switched to the Democrats in 2000 (and thus Jeffords probably wouldn't have jumped ship).  This is because the margin of victory for Democrats in those races was less than the number of votes for the Libertarian candidates.<br>
<br>
So if Republicans would do more to satisfy Libertarian concerns, they would win more elections...even the close ones.<br>
<br>
If God gives us freedom, why must man take it away. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#FFFF00>- </font><a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives>FCAV Conservatives</a><font color=#FFFF00> - </font><a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2>General Conservative Discussion</a> <font color=#FFFF00> - </font><a href="http://www.geocities.com/the_right_turn2003">FCAV</a><font color=#FFFF00> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.32<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

